Root cause is in [agent-session-runner.mjs](/Users/colinfreed/Projects/Experiments/agent-management-system-prototype/scripts/agent-session-runner.mjs#L50). Initial runs call `codex exec ... --sandbox <mode>`, but follow-up runs call `codex exec resume ...` without reapplying the stored sandbox. The session still persists the chosen sandbox in [agent-sessions.ts](/Users/colinfreed/Projects/Experiments/agent-management-system-prototype/src/lib/server/agent-sessions.ts#L477) and [agent-sessions.ts](/Users/colinfreed/Projects/Experiments/agent-management-system-prototype/src/lib/server/agent-sessions.ts#L527), so the UI keeps showing `workspace-write` even though resumed runs fall back to the CLI default, which is effectively read-only.

The fix is to map the stored sandbox onto the resume-specific flags that `codex exec resume --help` exposes:

```js
function buildCodexArgs(config) {
	const args = [];

	if (config.mode === 'message') {
		args.push('exec', 'resume', '--json', '--skip-git-repo-check');

		if (config.sandbox === 'workspace-write') {
			args.push('--full-auto');
		} else if (config.sandbox === 'danger-full-access') {
			args.push('--dangerously-bypass-approvals-and-sandbox');
		}

		if (config.model) {
			args.push('-m', config.model);
		}

		args.push(config.threadId, '-o', config.messagePath, config.prompt);
		return args;
	}

	// existing start-session path stays as-is
}
```

I tried to apply that directly, but this turn’s host sandbox is read-only, so writes were rejected. That reproduces the exact class of problem you described. If you reopen me in a write-enabled session, I can land this patch and add a regression test in [agent-sessions.spec.ts](/Users/colinfreed/Projects/Experiments/agent-management-system-prototype/src/lib/server/agent-sessions.spec.ts#L1) so resume args are covered for `read-only`, `workspace-write`, and `danger-full-access`.
